Rating: 4
This was fantastic and really quick to cook as well. I had no problem getting the scallops to brown but I did give the raw scallops a good hard squeeze in paper towels before I started which seemed to do the trick. The sauce did take a while to thicken but I left the oven on at 70C (I think that's about 160F...) and left the scallops in there whilst I did the sauce. I also left the vegetable stir-fry which I made earlier to serve the scallops on, plus the serving plates, which seemed to solve the problem of things going a bit tepid during the wait. The extra time this bought me allowed me to add more orange juice and reduce it down further, so the sugar was all from the oranges and the sauce therefore more intensely orangey. I agree about the chilli (I added a couple of de-seeded chillis in there!) and about using sesame oil rather than groundnut/peanut oil. I also found a good slug of Worcestershire sauce gave it a nice kick.

Rating: 1
Just okay in our book. It is impossible to brown scallops in a skillet. They give off so much liquid and you certainly don't need to oil the pan. Also, the searing time is way too long for average size scallops, especially when you pour the hot glaze over them after they've been sitting for a few minutes. The glaze takes more than 2 minutes to reduce/thicken and it still was more saucy than a glaze but it did have good flavor.

